<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-365-248  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 365 248.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>The Office  June 1989 v109 n6 p78(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>What the automated office needs: planning. (ergonomically designedfurniture)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Kwiecinski, Gordon F.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Ergonomically designed furniture is a growing concern in officeautomation.andP;  Office automation provides an opportunity to addressissues such as efficient use of space, improved workflow,lighting, air quality, noise reduction and improved productivity.andO;Ergonomics is especially important, as is indicated by recentlegislative initiatives.andP;  For example, Suffolk County, NY, nowrequires detachable keyboards, adjustable furniture, work breaksand eye care for employees who use terminals.andP;  The importance ofergonomics and the office environment means that these issuesshould be considered early in the design of a new facility.andO;Employee input is essential in the design process.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     FurnitureErgonomicsOffice EquipmentWorkstationsVDTsSuffolk County, New York.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>